					2006-05-09
				
			
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="blcontent copy">
		<h1>Pizza Reaches New Heights in San Fran</h1>
		
			<h2>Dateline: San Francisco, CA </h2>
		
		<div id="ddCopy" class="copy">
			For all its rich Italian roots and superb restaurants, San Francisco long suffered from a culinary failing: The pizza was consistently subpar. Most local pizzerias turned out dense, leaden discs, overdosed with toppings, with all the taste and texture of the box they came in. They were pies that would have made your <I>nonna</I> cry &#151; frat-boy belly-filler rather than actual food. Recently, though, Bay Area restaurateurs have been rolling out a different kind of pizza &#151; pizza as the Neapolitans intended, with thin, blistered crusts and fresh, light toppings. These days in San Francisco and across the bay in Berkeley and Oakland  you can find pizza that they'd proudly eat in Napoli. Or New York. Here, the "fab four" of SF pizzerias: <BR><BR>
<B>A16:</B> Named for a highway that cuts through the bottom of the Boot, A16 serves rustic, Campanian dishes such as braised pork breast with olives, herbs, and chestnuts, and tuna conserva (preserved in olive oil) served with dandelion greens. But what really packs the crowds in at this spot in the upscale Marina district are the pizzas, cooked quickly in a wood-fired oven just until the edges bubble and blackened welts mottle the bottom of the crust. Purists should go for the pizza Margherita &#151; a simple, classic beauty &#151; while meat-lovers will appreciate the house-cured pancetta on the Treviso pie. (2355 Chestnut St.; 415-771-2261; www.a16sf.com)<BR><BR>
<B>Delfina Pizzeria:</B> One of the city's most popular Italian restaurants has sired a tiny pizzeria right next door. As he does at Delfina, chef Craig Stoll keeps things simple, with thin, crisp crusts and toppings applied in moderation. If there's a guiding star on the small constellation of pies on the menu it's the pizza Napoletana dotted with anchovies, capers, and olives and refreshingly free of cheese. Salads and sides such as perky eggplant caponata are in keeping with the overall high standards. At this popular Mission district outpost, the only risk is whether you'll get a seat. (3611 18th St.; 415-437-6800; www.pizzeriadelfina.com)<BR><BR>
<B>Pizzaiolo:</B> Across the bay in Oakland, former Chez Panisse chef Charlie Hallowell tends the oven at this bustling new neighborhood restaurant where exposed brick walls and an open kitchen lend the atmosphere a touch of urban chic. Service in the dining room can be sluggish, but a seat at the bar is an appealing option. You can sip from a short list of Italian wines and watch the flames blister your pizza. The near-perfect pies are pillowy around the rim and crisp on the bottom. Topped with house-made fennel sausage, chicory, and other ingredients that shift with the seasons, they make a light meal for two or a robust feast for one. (5008 Telegraph Ave., Oakland; 510-652-4888; www.pizzaiolo.us)<BR><BR>

<B>Gioia Pizzeria:</B> At this hole-in-the-wall in Berkeley, whole pies and slices are served through a hole in the wall. Actually, it's a window, but you get the drift. Will Gioia grew up in Park Slope, Brooklyn, and migrated west where the weather was better but the pizza was worse. Gioia has helped change that with a pizzeria that pays homage to both coasts. While the organic flour crusts and arugula and pesto toppings may please the disciples of Alice Waters, the crisp, airy slices and tangy tomato sauce give New York transplants a taste of home. (1586 Hopkins St., Berkeley, CA; 510-528-4692)
		</div>
		
			<p class="copy">
				&mdash; 
				
					Josh Sens
				
				
				
			</p>
		
		
		
